summary.seg: This manuscript is an Acts and Epistles book, probably produced in the later 12th or earlier 13th century, possibly in Cyprus or the Levant. This is suggested by the black ink used for the main text, common in that region, and the script's combination of features suggestive of a 13th-century date with others not usually found after the first half of the 12th century. Such a combination would be plausible in a manuscript produced outside the Byzantine mainstream, where features of style could linger after falling from favour in the core of the Greek-speaking world, even while other more up-to-date tendencies were adopted.

By the standards of such New Testament manuscripts it is a simple production with little ornamentation. It includes introductory hypotheses to the Pauline Epistles, but not to the Catholic Epistles. Its rubricated headings to books and hypotheses include not only the basic title of the text, but also usually some contextual information, which in the case of the hypotheses is normally treated as part of the main text rather than as prefatory material. A number of the epistles are also provided with closing subscriptions, in some cases including a standard count of the number of lines (stichoi). The manuscript has suffered some losses, principally that of the first three quires, while a few of its folios have been rebound out of order.

msItem.title: Act and Epistles book
msItem.note: Defective at the beginning and end.
Gregory-Aland 309; Von Soden α 351 (K x); Scrivener Act. 21
msItem.filiation: The manuscript was categorised by Aland as conforming to the majority text. It has been used in the Nestle-Aland, UBS, Vogels and Souter editions.

msItem.title: Acts of the Apostles
msItem.note: Defective at the beginning and end ( Ac 12:2-28:31)
msItem.incipit: f. 1r Ἰάκωβον τὸν ἀδελφὸν

msItem.title: Letter of James
msItem.rubric: f. 35v Ἐπιστολὴ τοῦ ἁγίου ἀποστόλου Ἰακώβου, καθολική: Περὶ ὑπομονῆς καὶ πίστεως ἀνεποκρίτου καὶ ταπεινοφροσύνης, πρὸς τοὺς πλουσίως

msItem.finalRubric: f. 40v Τοῦ ἁγίου ἀποστόλου Ἰακώβου ἐπιστολὴ, στίχων σμβʹ

msItem.title: First Letter of Peter
msItem.rubric: f. 41r Πέτρου ἐπιστολὴ αʹ· Περὶ τῆς ἐν Χριστῶ ἀναγεννήσεως· καὶ περὶ ὑπομονῆς καὶ πειρασμοῦ καὶ περὶ σωτηρίωδους πίστεως, προκατηγγελμένης ὑπὸ τῶν προφήτων

msItem.explicit: f. 46r ἐν φιλίματι ἀγάπης· εἰρήνη ὑμῖν· πᾶσι τοῖς ἐν Χριστῶ Ἰησοῦ, ἀμήν (1 Pe 5:14)
msItem.finalRubric: f. 46r Πέτρου ἐπιστολὴ καθολικὴ αʹ ἐγράφη ἀπὸ Ῥώμης, στίχων σλϛʹ

msItem.title: Second Letter of Peter
msItem.rubric: f. 46r Πέτρου ἐπιστολὴ, βʹ· Περὶ κλήσεως τῆς ἐν πίστει βεβαιουμένης ἐρ.. τοῖς τῆς ἀρετῆς καὶ ἐλπίδος τῶν μελλόντων ἀγαθῶν
msItem.incipit: f. 46r Συμεὼν Πέτρος· δοῦλος καὶ ἀπόστολος Ἰησοῦ Χριστοῦ
msItem.explicit: f. 50r αὐτῶ ἡ δόξα καὶ εἰς ἡμέραν αἰῶνος, ἀμήν
msItem.finalRubric: f. 50r Τοῦ ἁγίου ἀποστόλου Πέτρου ἐπιστολὴ, βʹ

msItem.title: First Letter of John
msItem.rubric: f. 50r Ἰωάννου ἐπιστολὴ, αʹ Εὐαγγελικὴ θεολογία Χριστοῦ
msItem.incipit: f. 50r Ὃ ἦν ἀπαρχῆς ὃ ἀκηκόαμεν· ὃ ἑωράκαμεν τοῖς ὀφθαλμοῖς ἡμῶν

msItem.finalRubric: f. 56r Ἰωάννου εὐαγγελιστοῦ, ἐπιστολὴ αʹ ἐγράφη ἀπὸ Ἐφέσου, στίχων οδʹ

msItem.title: Second Letter of John
msItem.rubric: f. 56r Τοῦ αὐτοῦ ἐπιστολὴ, βʹ Προοίμιον περὶ ὀρθοῦ βίου ἐν ἀγάπη Θεοῦ διὰ πίστεως εὐσεβοῦς ἀμεταθέτου
msItem.incipit: f. 56r Ὁ πρεσβύτερος ἐκλεκτὴ κυρία καὶ τοῖς τέκνοις αὐτῆς
msItem.explicit: f. 57r ἀσπάζεταί σε τὰ τέκνα τῆς ἀδελφῆς σου· τῆς ἐκλεκτῆς, ἀμήν
msItem.finalRubric: f. 57r Τοῦ ἁγίου ἀποστόλου Ἰωάννου ἐπιστολὴ, στίχων λʹ

msItem.title: Third Letter of John
msItem.rubric: f. 57r Ἰωάννου ἐπιστολὴ καθολικῆ, γʹ:- Εὐχὴ ὑπὲρ τελειώσεως καὶ εὐχαριστίας ἐφομολογία φιλοξενίας τῶν άδελφῶν, διὰ Χριστόν
msItem.incipit: f. 57r Ὁ πρεσβύτερος Γαΐω τῶ ἀγαπητῶ· ὃν ἐγὼ ἀγαπῶν ἐν ἀληθεία
msItem.explicit: f. 58r ἀσπάζονταί σε οἱ φίλοι· ἀσπάζου τοὺς φίλους κατ'ὄνομα
msItem.finalRubric: f. 58r Τοῦ ἁγίου Ἰωάννου τοῦ ἀποστόλου ἐπιστολὴ γʹ, στίχων λβʹ

msItem.title: Letter of Jude
msItem.rubric: f. 58r Ἰούδα ἐπιστολή καθολική:- Περὶ προσοχῆς τῆς εἰς Χριστὸν πίστεως· διὰ τὴν ἐπανάστασιν τῶν ἀσεβῶν καὶ ἀσελγῶν ἀνδρῶν

msItem.explicit: f. 59v καὶ νῦν καὶ εἰς πάντας τοὺς αἴωνας, ἀμήν
msItem.finalRubric: f. 59v Τοῦ ἁγίου ἀποστόλου Ἰούδα ἐπιστολὴ στίχων ξηʹ

msItem.title: Letter to the Romans
msItem.rubric: f. 60r Εὐαγγελικὴ διδασκαλία περὶ τῶν ἔξω χάριτος Χριστοῦ καὶ τῶν έν χάριτι· καὶ περὶ ἐλπίδος καὶ πολιτεύας πνευματικῆς:- Πρὸς Ῥωμαίους
msItem.incipit: f. 60r Παῦλος δοῦλος Ἰησοῦ Χριστοῦ κλητὸς ἀπόστολος· ἀφωρισμένος εἰς εὐαγγέλιον Θεοῦ
msItem.explicit: f. 79r ἡ χάρις τοῦ Κυρίου ἡμῶν Ἰησοῦ Χριστοῦ· μετὰ πάντων ὑμῶν, ἀμήν

msItem.explicit: f. 84r καὶ περὶ εὐλογίας τῆς εἰς τοὺς ἁγίους παραγγέλλει· καὶ οὕτως τελειοῖ τὴν ἐπιστολήν

msItem.title: First Letter to the Corinthians
msItem.rubric: f. 84r Πρὸς Κορινθίους αʹ· Περὶ πλειόνων καὶ διαφόρων ἡ ἐπιστολὴ διόρθωσιν ἔχουσα τῶν Κορινθιοις ἡμαρτηκότων

msItem.rubric: f. 160v Ἔπαινος Φιλίμονος καὶ εὐχαριστίαν ὑπὲρ αὐτοῦ: Πρὸς Φιλίμονα
msItem.incipit: f. 160v Παῦλος δέσμιος Χριστοῦ Ἰησοῦ· καὶ Τιμόθεος ἀδελφὸς· Φιλίμονι τῶ ἀγαπητῶ
msItem.explicit: f. 160v καὶ τῆ κατ οἶκον σου ἐκκλησίᾳ

support.material: Parchment (FHHF), of thin to medium thickness and medium quality. There are occasional small holes dating to the time of production, but none within the written surface.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript is foliated with the numbers i-iv + 1-160 + v-viii in pencil, in Arabic and Roman numerals, recto, upper right.
Every tenth folio (1, 11, 21 etc) has also been numbered in pencil, in Arabic numerals, recto, lower right.

A few folios (e.g. ff. 79r-85v) have been foliated with Arabic numerals in black ink, recto, lower right. This sequence does not count the stub which the later foliation numbers as f. 82, and where the two sequences conflict, these numbers have sometimes been struck through with pencil.

collation.p: The manuscript consists of 21 quires, all quaternia.

list.item: Quire 18-2 ff. 1-6 The first and last folios have been lost, with loss of text.

Quire 118-3 ff. 79-84 The original sixth and seventh folios have been lost, as has most of the third, with loss of text. The surviving leaves have been bound out of order. The original order was ff. 80-82, 79, 84, two lost folios, f. 83.
Quire 218-4 ff. 157-160 The first, third, sixth and eighth folios have been lost, with loss of text.

signatures.p: There are orignal quire signatures in Greek numerals, in black ink, on the first folio of each quire, recto, lower left, and the last folio of each quire, verso, lower right. The first three quires have been lost, so the numbers of these signatures are always larger than their actual place in the present sequence by three. They survive on Quires 2-20 (εʹ-κγʹ).
Modern quire signatures in Arabic numerals, in pencil, have been added to the first folio of each quire, recto, lower right. These number the quires according to the present state of the manuscript.

supportDesc.condition: The upper part of f. 82 and most of the following folio have been torn away, and there are numerous small holes and small tears to the edges of other folios. There are extensive areas of purple mould, which has rendered much of the text illegible (e.g. 71v-92r). There are also brown and red stains, areas of dirt and significant discoloration (e.g. ff. 15r-17r, 39v-40r). Substantial areas of text have faded into illegibility, and some of these have been overwritten with black ink (e.g. ff. 6r-7r). There is significant cockling of the leaves.

layoutDesc.layout:
A single column of 24-27 lines. 110 100
Pricking sometimes survives on all three edges, but some has been lost to cropping. Ruled in hardpoint, system Leroy 1, type Leroy 00C1. Text hangs from the lines.

handNote.p: The main text has been copied by Hand A in an upright scribal Mi-Fettaugen mixed minuscule script, in black ink. There is significant variation in letter size and frequent flourishing of tails into the margins.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear throughout the line. Breathings are round or occasionally angular, and mute iota is absent or adscript. There is occasional decorative use of the double dot, and accentuation of all nomina sacra. Accents are sometimes joined to letters and breathings. The double grave accent is in use.

The modern eta and flat-bottomed omega are present, and there are inclusions of letters within omicron. Lines joining a letter, particularly alpha and rho, to the following letter, are sometimes greatly elongated.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, lower and middle commas, question mark and full stop.
This hand has also provided the rubric, in red ink in a similar style, sometimes including the opening phrases of the text of hypotheses as well as the conventional heading.
Subscriptions and some headings and incipits have been addd by Hand B in an upright scribal mixed minuscule script making containing a large proportion of majuscule letters, in red ink.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear throughout the line. Breathings are round or occasionally angular, and mute iota is absent. There is occasional decorative use of the double dot, and accentuation of all nomina sacra.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, lower and middle commas and full stop.
Some headings has been written by the same hand in epigraphic display majuscule script, in red ink, distinguishing these from the rubricated incipit.

decoNote.p: The text of each book or hypothesis and of various subsections within these begin with a minor initial in red ink.

additions.p: Occasional marginal lection notes and other annotations in Greek have been added by various later hands (e.g. ff. 55r, 84r, 94v). These include the name Demetrios Batas (Διμιτρις του Βατα) on f. 141v, which may be an indication of ownership.
An ownership note has been added on f. 1r by Kosmas Phrochmos (or Phromchos): Κοσμᾶ Φρομχου κήρυκος εὐαγγελικου.
Another hand has added in the margins of f. 76r the text of Romans 11:22-29, which had been omitted by the copyist.
Notes in Latin have been added regarding lost or incorrectly bound folios.
A note of the contents in Latin has been added on f. iv verso, with an addition by another hand, who also added the initials C.B.S. to this folio.
The ownership note Jo. Luke has been added to the left pastedown.

binding.p: Full leather binding over couched-laminate boards, with an 18th-century pale brown leather spine and reused 17th-century boards, with dark brown leather covering and plain pastedowns. There is decorative gold tooling on the outer surface and edges of the boards, and on the spine. The classmark is tooled in gold on the spine, along with the title Act. Apost. &c. M.C. on a label. The edges have been painted black.
binding.condition: There is a break in each endband.

history.origin: The characteristics of the script suggest that the manuscript was probably produced in the last quarter of the 12th century or the first half of the 13th, perhaps in the Levant or in Cyprus. Such a date is suggested by the general appearance of the script, notably its variation in letter size, but the adscript form of the mute iota and the presence of angular breathings would not usually be expected after the middle of the 12th century. However, the very black ink used is typical of manuscripts from the south-eastern Mediterranean, and the type of script would also be consistent with such an origin. In this case, the persistence of more archaic features could reflect production in a peripheral region lagging behind metropolitan trends.

provenance.p: Possibly owned by Demetrios Batas Batas, Demetrios
